<H1><CENTER>Demonstration 3</CENTER></H1>
<HR>

This demonstration illustrates a simple character reader.
I have created the digits 0-9 as 5x5 patterns, and trained a network
to recognize these patterns.  This demonstration has a GUI which 
displays the pattern and allows it to be interactively manipulated.
You can submit the updated pattern to the NN and immediately see
the results.  

<P>

<IMG SRC="./bpdemo3gui.png" ALT="Demo3 GUI">

<P>
You can toggle the settings on the "Pattern Edit" panel and submit
these changes to the NN and immediately see the classification.
This is interesting because it allows you to quickly discover how
tolerant the NN is of noisy images.

<P>
This network has 25 input nodes (one for each pixel of a 5x5 input),
5 middle nodes and 10 output nodes (one for each image I want to
match).

<P>
The training set looks like this:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="./zero_a.txt">zero</A>
<LI><A HREF="./one_a.txt">one</A>
<LI><A HREF="./two_a.txt">two</A>
<LI><A HREF="./three_a.txt">three</A>
<LI><A HREF="./four_a.txt">four</A>
<LI><A HREF="./five_a.txt">five</A>
<LI><A HREF="./six_a.txt">six</A>
<LI><A HREF="./seven_a.txt">seven</A>
<LI><A HREF="./eight_a.txt">eight</A>
<LI><A HREF="./nine_a.txt">nine</A>
</UL>

<P>
To recreate the demo:

<OL>
<LI>This demonstration requires that you obtain the source tree
    because you will need the ASCII digit files.
<LI>Compile the sources, ensure that your $CLASSPATH reflects
    the location of the class files.
<LI>Your current directory should be where the 'build.xml' file 
    is located.
<LI>java com.digiburo.backprop1b.demo3.GenerateDatum (to convert data from ASCII files to serialized PatternList, produces file 'demo3.trn')
<LI>java com.digiburo.backprop1b.demo3.Trainer (to train network, produces file 'demo3.serial')
<LI>java com.digiburo.backprop1b.demo3.BpDigitTestGui (to run GUI)
</OL>

